abstract: "Nematostella vectensis have already been found to have advanced circadian rhythms, the ability to reproduce sexually or asexually, and the ability to repair seemingly life-threatening injuries. Even with that knowledge, their sex determination mechanism, or even the sex ratio of a clutch, has yet to be found. The focus of this experiment was to determine sex ratio in these up-and-coming model organisms. To conduct this experiment, three temperature conditions (17°C, 21°C, and 26°C) were selected to raise offspring. Three clutches of eggs were collected, fertilized, and placed into a temperature control. Even though the oldest of these offspring were not even a month old yet, there have been some stark differences between the 17°C offspring and the warmer temperature offspring. The 21°C and 26°C replicates are developing much faster than the 17°C offspring. This ongoing experiment will be completed when offspring reach sexual maturity and spawn for the first time, allowing for male and female identification."
